    "body": "# The Light That Never Moved\n\nLook around you for a moment.\n\nYou can see your hands. You can see the room, the screen, the light coming in. Close your eyes and you can still notice things. A sound somewhere. The weight of your body in the chair. The breath going in and out. Thoughts arriving, one after another, like weather.\n\nEverything on that list has something in common. Every single thing you have ever experienced has been something you noticed. An object, held in front of you. Seen, heard, felt, thought.\n\nSo here is a simple question, and it is going to be stranger than it sounds.\n\nWho is doing the noticing?\n\nNot the hands. The hands are noticed. Not the thoughts. The thoughts are noticed too. Behind all of it, there is the one who sees. Can you turn around and look at that one?\n\nGo on. Try. I will wait.\n\n## The thing you cannot catch\n\nYou cannot do it. And the reason you cannot is the most important thing you will hear today.\n\nEverything you have ever known has appeared in front of awareness, like an image on a screen. But awareness itself has never once shown up as one of those images. You cannot see the seer. You cannot observe the observer. The moment you turn to look for it, all you find is more looking.\n\nThis is not a failure of effort. It is structural. A knife is sharp, but it cannot cut itself. An eye can see the whole world, but it cannot see itself seeing. A torch lights up everything in the room, but it cannot shine its beam back on its own source. The thing that reveals everything is the one thing it can never make into an object.\n\nYou are that. The light that shows everything and is itself never shown.\n\n## The oldest question\n\nThere is an ancient text that is built entirely around this, and it does not waste a word.\n\nIt is called the केनोपनिषद् (Kenopanishad). केन (kena) means by whom, or by what. And the whole thing opens by refusing the obvious question. It does not ask what you see. It asks what makes the seeing possible.\n\nश्रोत्रस्य श्रोत्रं मनसो मनो यद्\nवाचो ह वाचं स उ प्राणस्य प्राणः\nचक्षुषश्चक्षुः\n\nThe ear of the ear. The mind of the mind. The speech of speech. The breath of the breath. The eye of the eye.\n\nSit with that phrase. The eye of the eye. There is the eye that sees the tree. And then there is whatever it is that makes the eye able to see at all. The seeing behind the seeing. The hearing that makes hearing possible. That is what the whole text is pointing at, and it points by refusing to let you grab it.\n\n## Try it for yourself\n\nDo not take my word for any of this. The tradition never wanted your belief. It wanted your looking.\n\nSo here is the experiment. Notice a sound right now. Any sound. The hum of the room, your own breath, anything.\n\nNow, instead of the sound, find the one who is hearing it.\n\nNotice what happens. You cannot find a hearer sitting there as a thing. You only find more hearing. Reach for the one who sees, and there is only more seeing. The witness moves back exactly as far as you reach for it, every time, because it is not the thing being reached for. It is the reaching itself.\n\nThis is what नेति नेति (neti neti) means. Not this, not this. Every time you find something, you can say, that is not it, because I just saw it. The body, not it, you can observe the body. The thoughts, not it, you can watch the thoughts come and go. The feelings, not it. Keep going, and you do not arrive at a final object. You arrive at the one doing the looking, which can never be looked at.\n\n## The one thing that never changed\n\nNow here is where it turns from a puzzle into something that can quietly change your life.\n\nEverything you can notice is always changing. Your body is not the body you had as a child. Your moods pass like weather, none of them staying. Your thoughts churn all day and are gone. The entire world streams past, never the same for two moments together.\n\nBut the awareness in which all of that appears does not change.\n\nThink back to yourself as a small child. The body was different. The thoughts were different. The whole world looked different. But the bare fact of being aware, the simple sense of being the one to whom things appear, that has not changed at all. The contents of your life have been swapped out completely, many times over. The seeing has been constant the entire time.\n\nYou at five, at twenty, at fifty. Utterly different films. The same light falling on the screen.\n\nThat is why this text matters. Everything you have ever worried about losing belongs to the part that was always changing anyway. And the one thing that was truly you, the seeing itself, was never once in danger, because it never moved.\n\n## The honest not-knowing\n\nThe केनोपनिषद् (Kenopanishad) has one more turn, and it is the most beautiful, because it protects you from the worst mistake.\n\nIt says, in effect, the one who thinks he knows it does not know it. And the one who knows he cannot know it, knows.\n\nThis sounds like a riddle. It is not. It is a warning. The moment you believe you have grasped the witness, caught it, pinned it down as a thing you understand, you have made it into just another object. And it was never an object. So your certainty is the proof you missed it. The honest position, the one that says I cannot make this into something I hold, that is the one standing closest to the truth.\n\nThis is the seeking tradition being consistent to the very end. It will not hand you a conclusion to memorise. It walks you to the window and lets you see for yourself, and then tells you that the seeing cannot be turned into a souvenir.\n\n## Where this leaves you\n\nYou have spent your whole life looking for things. Better situations, answers, the next experience. That is fine. That is what a life is partly made of.\n\nThis is the one thing you cannot look for. Because it is the looking. You cannot go and find it, the way you find your keys. You can only stop, for a moment, and notice that it has never once been absent. Through every good day and every terrible one, through every version of you that has come and gone, it has been here. Quiet. Unmoving. The light by which all of it appeared.\n\nIt is here right now. It is the one reading these words. Not the words, the reader. Not the thoughts about the reader, the one noticing those too.\n\nThe eye of the eye.\n\nThe light never moved. It is shining on this very sentence, turning these marks into meaning, and it has been doing that, without effort and without pause, your entire life.\n\nThat. That is what you are.",
    "excerpt": "Look around you for a moment. You can see your hands. You can see the room, the screen, the light coming in. Close your eyes and you can still notice things. A sound somewhere. The weight of your body in the chair. The breath going in and out. Thoughts arriving, one after another, like weather.",
